5|$|In August 2009 the SNP {{proposed}} {{a bill to}} hold <b>a</b> <b>referendum</b> <b>on</b> independence in November 2010. Opposition from all other major parties led to an expected defeat. After the 2011 elections gave the SNP an overall majority in the Scottish Parliament, <b>a</b> <b>referendum</b> <b>on</b> independence for Scotland was held on 18 September 2014. The referendum resulted in a rejection of independence, by 55.3% to 44.7%. During the campaign, the three main parties in the UK Parliament pledged to extend {{the powers of the}} Scottish Parliament. An all-party commission chaired by Lord Smith of Kelvin was formed, which led to a further devolution of powers through the Scotland Act 2016.|$|E
5|$|In Quebec, the 1994 provincial {{election}} {{brought the}} sovereigntist Parti Québécois back to power, led by Jacques Parizeau. The party's platform promised to hold <b>a</b> <b>referendum</b> <b>on</b> sovereignty during his {{term in office}} as premier. The PQ won a majority government with 44.75% of the popular vote.|$|E
5|$|On 19 May 1991, the Croatian {{authorities}} held <b>a</b> <b>referendum</b> <b>on</b> independence {{with the}} option of remaining in Yugoslavia as a looser union. Serb local authorities issued calls for a boycott, which were largely followed by Croatian Serbs. The referendum passed with 94% in favor.|$|E
